In your `toString()` method you set `temp=0`, then in the while loop you have the condition `while(queue[temp]!=null)`, which means this loop is looking at the very start of the array `queue` and checking if it&#39;s `null`, rather than the first element which is indexed by `frontIndex`. When you dequeue the first time, you&#39;re setting the first index in the array to be `null`, which then causes the `while` loop in your `toString()` method to not even run due to the condition `while(queue[temp]!=null)`.
Instead of setting `temp=0`, set it as `temp=frontIndex` and this should print your queue as expected.

```
@Override
public String toString() {
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
    int temp = frontIndex;
    sb.append(&quot;queue: ( &quot;);
    if(queue.length == 0) {
        sb.append(&quot;empty queue&quot;);
    }
    while(queue[temp]!=null) {
        sb.append(queue[temp].toString());
        sb.append(&quot;---&gt;&quot;);
        temp++;
    }
    sb.append(&quot;)&quot;);
    return sb.toString();
}
```

